# MLT Experience

The example we will use in this Experience Lab comes from the IoT industry. We have an engine with 45 sensors, data from which we receive periodically. The engine has two states which we must predict:

- 0 - normal operation
- 1 - engine problems

Note: The training dataset already contains the engine state, so we can train our model on it.

There is already an ML model that predicts the state of the engine, and InterSystems IRIS™ automatically validates and retrains the model if prediction quality falls below an adjustable threshold.

The goals of this Experience Lab are for you to:

-	See how automated AI/ML pipeline – an automated solution that produces predictions – works in InterSystems IRIS.
- Improve the ML model predicting the state of the engine.


For successful completion of this Experience, it is recommended (but not mandatory) for you to be familiar with:

- [InterSystems IRIS Data Platform](https://learning.intersystems.com/course/view.php?name=InterSystems%20IRIS%20QuickStart)
- [Principal Component Analysis](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principal_component_analysis)
- [Logistic Regression](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_regression)
- [Mean squared error](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mean_squared_error)
- [Python](https://docs.python.org/3/tutorial/index.html)

## Exercise 1. Production

First, let's get familiar with the production. 

### Steps: 

1. Open [Production Management page](/csp/python/EnsPortal.ProductionConfig.zen).

 ![](data:image/png;base64,)
 
On this page you will see the main components of the AI/ML production:

- `py.ens.Operation` – Executes Python code and sends back the results.
- `ml.engine.TrainProcess` – Trains a new prediction model.
- `ml.engine.PredictService` – Receives information from engine sensors and sends it to `ml.engine.PredictProcess` to predict engine state. At the moment, `ml.engine.PredictService` is disabled (gray) and does not transfer data.
- `ml.engine.PredictProcess` – Uses the ML model created by `ml.engine.TrainProcess` to predict engine state.
- `ml.engine.CheckService` – Regularly checks the accuracy of the ML model by comparing predictions against the real engine state. If the prediction error rate is above the threshold, the service sends a request to the `ml.engine.TrainProcess` to update the model.
- `ml.engine.InitService` – Sends a request to the `ml.engine.TrainProcess` to train the initial model at production start.

Each business host has relevant settings under `ML` category.

## Exercise 2. Explore ml.engine.CheckService

Let's start with model validation. `ml.engine.CheckService` regularly verifies the accuracy of the ML model. The service compares new predictions to the true state of the engine and calculates the percentage of errors by comparing the last one thousand predictions to the true data. If the error rate is above the threshold (an adjustable setting), `ml.engine.CheckService` sends a request to the `ml.engine.TrainProcess` to retrain the model.

### Steps

1. On the [Production Management page](/csp/python/EnsPortal.ProductionConfig.zen) click `ml.engine.CheckService`. 
2. Click `Log in` on the menu on the right. 

You will see the results of model validation displayed there.

 ![](data:image/png;base64,)
 
In the screenshot, you can see that at the beginning there are no predictions to validate the model, as `ml.engine.PredictService` is disabled.

## Exercise 3. Start ml.engine.PredictService

After checking the model accuracy with `ml.engine.CheckService`, now we move on to `ml.engine.PredictService`, which retrieves new data from sensors and sends it to `ml.engine.PredictProcess` for new predictions.

### Steps

1. Return to the [Production Management page](/csp/python/EnsPortal.ProductionConfig.zen).
2. Double-click the `ml.engine.PredictService`.
3. When prompted, enable  `ml.engine.PredictService`.
4. The service status indicator for `ml.engine.PredictService` should turn green.
5. Select `ml.engine.PredictService` > `Messages`. 
6. Click the `Go to Message Viewer` link:

 ![](data:image/png;base64,)
 
Or open the [Message Viewer](/csp/python/EnsPortal.MessageViewer.zen?SOURCEORTARGET=ml.engine.PredictService). In the Message Viewer, you can look at the messages generated by `ml.engine.PredictService`.

7. Select any message and click the session link:

 ![](data:image/png;base64,)
 
In the Visual Trace window, which displays information about the interaction of production elements, we can see something like this:

 ![](data:image/png;base64,)

`ml.engine.PredictService` sends the new record id to `ml.engine.PredictProcess` to predict the condition of the engine [1].

`ml.engine.PredictProcess` causes Python Operation `isc.py.ens.Operation` to:
 
 - Load the row into Python [2].
 - Remove unused row properties [4].
 - Use the trained model to predict the engine state based on loaded sensor data [6].
 - Indicate successful completion of a request via empty answers from `isc.py.ens.Operation` [3] and [5].
 - Return the predicted engine state in JSON format [7].

`ml.engine.PredictProcess` then parses JSON and returns the prediction back to `ml.engine.PredictService` [8].

### Bonus Points

You can open ml.engine.PredictProcess similarly to `ml.engine.TrainProcess` (see Exercise 4) from the [Production Management page](/csp/python/EnsPortal.ProductionConfig.zen) for more details on how prediction works or to check the Visual Trace for details.

## Exercise 4. Explore ml.engine.TrainProcess

Now let's move to the heart of our AI/ML production: `ml.engine.TrainProcess`. It is the core process of this Experience, as it trains a new predictive model from supplied data.

### Steps

1.	Select `ml.engine.TrainProcess` in the Process list, then click the magnifying glass in the settings.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

The [Process Editor page opens](/csp/python/EnsPortal.BPLEditor.zen?BP=ml.engine.TrainProcess.bpl):

![](data:image/png;base64,)

This page shows the individual activities composing `ml.engine.TrainProcess`.

To view activity on the diagram, select the diagram and click the magnifying glass below the annotation.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

All the activities beginning with the word Wait are used to get results from asynchronous calls; you can ignore them.

2. Explore the following activities that comprise the process:

- Import - Load Python libraries.
- Load Data - Load the data for model training.
- Extract Y - Split the data into X (the independent variables) and Y (the dependent variable we are predicting).
- PCA - The [principal components](https://towardsdatascience.com/a-step-by-step-explanation-of-principal-component-analysis-b836fb9c97e2) calculation for X.
- CV - [Cross-validation](https://machinelearningmastery.com/k-fold-cross-validation/) of potential models.
- Fit - [Pipeline](https://www.kaggle.com/baghern/a-deep-dive-into-sklearn-pipelines) creation and training.

Annotations contain a more detailed description of activities and an explanation of their behaviors, alongside the Python code executed by `isc.py.ens.Operation`.

### Bonus Points

- What does the process receive as a request message?
- What settings are available for configuration?

The newer model at first produces good results – the error percentage goes down – for some time. However, after a while, the error percentage will go up again.

## Exercise 6. Improving the model

As you can see, our model does not work very well – it needs to be retrained frequently and error percentage is quite high.

Let's improve this model. 

### Steps

1. Open [ml.engine.TrainProcess](/csp/python/EnsPortal.BPLEditor.zen?BP=ml.engine.TrainProcess.bpl) (see Exercise 4).

In `CV` activity, we are gradually expanding the number of principal components used and then appending `mse` variable (for [Mean Squared Error](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mean_squared_error)) with the deviation of the logistic regression model built on a current subset of principal components:

 ![](data:image/png;base64,)

The output from this step is saved in the [Analytics Dashboard](/dsw/index.html#!/d/MSE.dashboard?ns=PYTHON).

However, this information remains unused anywhere else.

For example, based on `mse` variable we can build dependency graph for logistic regression model accuracy (y-axis, less is better), depending on the number of used principal components (x-axis) for the data set:

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

From the graph, it follows that for the best model we need to use not all principal components but the optimal number, which can vary.

2. Open the Fit activity.

 ![](data:image/png;base64,)

Here, we are creating a [pipeline](https://www.kaggle.com/baghern/a-deep-dive-into-sklearn-pipelines). 

3. Replace the line

```
pca = PCA()
```
With:
```
pca = PCA(n_components = 1 + mse.index(min(mse[1:])))
```

This will use not a complete set of principal components, but a subset of the ones that yielded the best `mse` result. To clarify:
To clarify:
- `mse[1:]` – Returns a subset of `mse` list with mean squared errors for each number of principal components.
- `min(list)` – Gets the minimum value from the `mse` list.
- `mse.index(value)` – Returns the position of the `value` in the `mse` list, which turns out to be exactly the number of principal components we need (minus one, since the list is zero based).
- Finally, we are creating a new [PCA](https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.decomposition.PCA.html) object specifying an `n_components` argument, for the number of components to keep. If `n_components` is not set, all components are kept.

After that, the pipeline will not use all principal components, just their optimal subset.

4. Make the necessary edits in the process, then click `Compile`.

5. After compilation is done, open the [Production Management page](/csp/python/EnsPortal.ProductionConfig.zen) and double-click the `ml.engine.TrainProcess` to load the new version of the process. In the dialog that appears, click `Restart`.

 ![](data:image/png;base64,)

## Exercise 7. Return to ml.engine.CheckService

Look at the `ml.engine.CheckService` Log or [Analytics Dashboard](/dsw/index.html#!/d/Monitor.dashboard?ns=PYTHON) Error levels.
As a new model uses an optimized principal component subset, the number of errors should go down after a while, as the last 1000 predictions are tested.

If there is no more new data, restart the production to start anew.

## Exercise 8. Further model improvements

How might you further improve the model? Different algorithms and strategies can help us to get a better performing model, which produces results with greater accuracy. Possible ideas include:

- Using [Decision Trees](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Decision_tree) – An easier-to-interpret alternative to regression; can provide better predictions in a broad range of situations
- Using [Cluster Analysis](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cluster_analysis) – Algorithms geared towards discrete prognosis
- Using [Naive Bayes Classifier](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Naive_Bayes_classifier) – Useful in situations that do not have a lot of data

## Summary

In this Experience, we saw how the automated AI/ML pipeline works in InterSystems IRIS and tried data science by improving the model. 

Additionally we demonstrated that InterSystems IRIS:

- Consolidates source data, models, and prediction results
- Orchestrates the process of launching, executing, and processing the results of AI/ML models using external mathematical modeling environments
- Makes it possible to robotize and automate the use of AI/ML tools
- Enables users to make real-time decisions to control the spontaneity and diversity of problem situations.
